:: Epilogue - Jane Dead Good {"position":"1100,2825","size":"100,100"}
Three months later, Walter White turned himself in.

Not to the DEA. Not to Hank. He drove to the police station on a Tuesday morning, asked for a cup of coffee, and waited.

The cancer had come back. Stage four. He'd known for six weeks.

He didn't want to die in the lab. He didn't want to die as Heisenberg.

(click: ?page)[==
The confession took four hours. Every name. Every corner. Every cook site.

Skyler kept the house. Flynn — Walter Jr. — didn't speak to his father for two years, and then he did.

It wasn't forgiveness. But it wasn't nothing.

(click: ?page)[==
Saul Goodman closed his practice on a Friday. His secretary wasn't surprised. 

He drove west until the highway ran out, then turned south, and kept going until New Mexico was a memory.

He opened a small practice in a small town where nobody knew his name.

That part, at least, he was good at.

(click: ?page)[==
